Report: Seehofer pushes for longer data retention
Data retention is currently suspended.
Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer, however, calls for an extension of the storage period after a media report.
He wants to strengthen the fight against child abuse.
Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer (CSU) calls for an extended data retention after a media report - instead of the planned ten weeks a half year.
As the "Bild am Sonntag" reports, Seehofer Justice Minister Christine Lambrecht (SPD) asked for a rapid amendment to the law in a letter.
Seehofer therefore wants to strengthen measures against child abuse.
He felt it would be useful to "make urgent adjustments to the law already now", the newspaper quotes from the letter.
Currently, data retention is suspended.
A decision of the ECJ is expected.
But Seehofer wants the amendments before, so that they can be applied immediately after a possible positive judgment, the report continues.
A spokesman for the Ministry of Justice told the newspaper that it was only reasonable to examine whether legal adjustments were necessary if the courts had decided.
In the fight against child abuse and child pornography, Seehofer, together with the interior ministers of the countries, had already spoken out in favour of data retention in June.
