Söder comments on the Corona situation after mass infection
Munich - Health Minister Melanie Huml (CSU) has already announced a Testoffensive for large farms on Sunday.
The press conference will be shown live on our homepage.
The case in Mamming, Dingolfing-Landau County, has frightened authorities and politics.
Almost 500 harvesters from several countries are currently working on the large vegetable farm, and more than a third have been infected with the Corona agent.
The farm is now under quarantine and is closed with a fence.
No one is allowed to leave the premises, food is delivered.
The authorities now offer free Corona tests to the 3300 inhabitants of the municipality.
Since the harvesters had little contact with the local population, the Landratsamt assumes so far that the infections did not spread beyond the farm.
"Knowledge Bisse": Confession of the alleged arsonist of Nantes
"My client has shown himself cooperative," said lawyer Quentin Chabert of the newspaper.
The defender added: "He greatly regrets the actions, the confession was a liberation for him".
His mandate was "straightened by a bit of conscience and greatly taken away by the extent of the destruction."
In the event of a conviction, according to the prosecutor's office, the man faces ten years of imprisonment and a fine of 150,000 euros.
The Gothic Saint Peter and Paul Cathedral in Nantes had been severely damaged during a fire on Saturday last week.
The fire had broken out in three distant places in the church.
Laboratory tests confirmed the suspicion of arson.
The suspect now detained had been arrested just a few hours after the fire.
He was released after a day.
The man works as a volunteer for the diocese of Nantes and was responsible for the closure of the cathedral on the eve of the fire.
Since there was no trace of a violent intrusion into the church, he quickly got into the eye of the investigators.
Discuss the abolition of the 50+1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thinking about abolishing the 50+1 rule.
"German football should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates completed facts," said Grindel of the "Bild am Sonntag".
He stressed: "The 50+1 rules do not work for the clubs that are most likely to become dangerous in Bavaria and Dortmund anyway: see Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In this respect, it is not possible to get around the debate whether it is not necessary to facilitate the involvement of investors in associations that want to break into this phalanx".
However, he had doubts as to whether there was a willingness in the German Football League to allow majority participations, which are prohibited in the Bundesliga by the 50+1 rule.
"It remains a legal risk to attract investment fences around the business location Bundesliga in a single European market," said Grindel.
The former DFB boss sees the danger that "the attempts to ensure a more competitive balance in the Bundesliga will ultimately only weaken the competitiveness of our top clubs at European level, but will not lead to more tension in the championship."
Even an equal distribution of TV money would not have a decisive effect.
"FC Bayern has a turnover of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund of 500 million and RB Leipzig of 300 million.
The differences are therefore already immense among the first three clubs alone.
The other 15 clubs have an average household of 130 million," said the 58-year-old.
Looking at the past, Grindel feels betrayed.
"Unfortunately, there were people who noticed this mistake and stabbed the press instead of addressing me," said Grindel about the acceptance of an expensive watch that had led to his resignation in April 2019.
"I've been very occupied with that human."
He had received the gift worth around 11,000 euros from a Ukrainian official.
"I committed a breach of compliance, and it was right to draw the consequences from it," said Grindel.
"With the ominous watch gift I have dealt completely transparently and unscrupulously.
Many people in the DFB knew about it."
He never "made a hel from the gift," the 58-year-old assured.
"That may be naive, at least this form of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption."
"Black Lives Matter": injured and a dead man
The protests against police violence in the United States have intensified again through Donald Trump's use of federal police in several cities.
On Saturday there were clashes between demonstrators and policemen in different cities.
Three people were injured in Louisville, and 16 were arrested in Seattle.
In Austin, a person was killed by gunfire while a demonstration train just crossed a crossroads.
Before that, there had been clashes in Portland during protests against racism and police violence.
The security forces, including federal police officers, used tear gas on Saturday night and violently dispersed demonstrators.
Hundreds of partially armed demonstrators marched through Louisville in Kentucky on Saturday, demanding that those responsible for Breonna Taylor's death be held accountable.
The 26-year-old student was shot dead at a drug razzia in her home in Louisville in March.
The raid was aimed at someone else who didn't live there, and no drugs were found.
On Saturday, when a member of a group called itself an armed alliance of black Americans fired a shot, three people were injured.
According to NBC, they were taken to the hospital.
None of them were in mortal danger.
The police set up barricades because local demonstrators of a white militia had also formed.
In the end, the two groups did not meet.
In Austin, Texas, a person was shot in the course of a Black Lives Matter demonstration and died.
The police reportedly took a suspect into custody.
It has not yet provided any detailed information on the circumstances of the action.
According to the New York Times, Mayor Steve Adler said that he was, like many in the city, "inwardly and stunned" because of what had happened.
In the American metropolis of Seattle, demonstrators also clashed with the police on Saturday.
They set fire to building cars in front of a youth prison, the police used glare grenades and pepper spray.
According to the "Seattle Times", 16 people were arrested for resisting police or assault.
A courthouse was set on fire in Oakland, California.
A small group of demonstrators broke windows, shot down fireworks, and blinded police officers with lasers, the Oakland police reported on late Saturday evening (local time).
The fire could be extinguished quickly.
In Aurora, a suburb of Denver in Colorado, a car drove through a crowd demonstrating on a highway.
According to the police, one of the demonstrators fired a gun and at least one person was taken to the hospital injured.
In addition, windows were smashed in a court and a fire was set, as the police reported.
Investigations have been initiated.
Rakoczy in Bad Kissingen: Historical costumes defy Corona
Although the big snack was missing in the spa town, visitors and actors enjoyed the Rakoczy flair of the alternative program.
It was unusual for visitors, actors and organisers: the Rakoczy weekend without a Rakoczy festival.
But: Even if the big party mile in the city center was missing, the crowds and program highlights like Saale burn, Rakoczy ball or parade, many of them were at their expense in the Corona-compliant alternative program.
"I think we managed to spread Rakoczy-Flair," says Kurdirektor Sylvie Thormann.
The guests would have accepted it well.
In principle, one goes back to the beginnings of the Rakoczy festival, when the historical ones alone were the focus of the festival.
Pleasant atmosphere
Vesna Konhäuser and her husband have always visited the Rakoczy Festival Bad Kissingen for more than 25 years.
So this time in the Corona year.
The couple has made themselves comfortable at the Luitpold Casino, observes the historical strolling and listens to Cuban live music at the casino restaurant.
"I also find it so pleasant," says Konhäuser.
She misses the crowds that don't belong to Rakoczy.
But you do not have the usual program highlights, above all Saale burns on Friday evening as well as the historic parade and the closing fireworks on Sunday evening.
"That's a shame.
The weather would have been great this year," she says.
Rakoczy tournament to take place again
For the actors of the historical spa guests, the alternative program partly meant more work.
For example, for Christina Gold, who participates in the parade in a normal year and can be seen there on the carriage of the spa garden café.
This year she was on Saturdays and Sundays in costume on foot in the city.
"It's more exhausting, otherwise we'll have it easier," she says.
The equestrian club had less to do, even if individual riders were on the way in the park.
"We very much hope that the rider quadrille will be allowed to take place again next year," says Chairman Ulrike Waldhofen.
She announced that after several years of intermission in 2021 a Rakoczy competition will take place again.
28 Corona cases with Spanish second division Fuenlabrada
The Spanish football side CF Fuenlabrada is slipping deeper into the crisis due to a Corona outbreak.
Since the newcomer from near Madrid had flown to the city of A Coruña in spite of the first Corona Falls on July 20th, one low blow follows the next.
Until Sunday 28 players or team members had been tested positively, one came to the hospital, as the club announced.
Fuenlabrada from the city of the same name south west of Madrid still had the chance to reach the ascent playoffs.
Now even the descent into the B-group of the second league threatens.
The match against Deportivo La Coruña last Monday was cancelled at the last moment, the prosecutor's office investigated for a possible offense against public health, the top sports authority CSD considering the forced descent of the club.
The players and other team members are in quarantine at a hotel.
"Until the sixth day of quarantine, they did not receive a fresh towel and gel," wrote the sports newspaper "AS".
Photos show how players hung underwear and club clothes in their rooms in the hotel for drying after apparently having to wash them themselves.
Also, the bed linen had not been changed for five days.
Another problem is food.
Neither good nor sufficient, wrote "AS".
The club management, on the other hand, said that they were satisfied with the hotel.
The club's lawyer, Javier Tebas Llanas, rejected the accusation of deliberately endangering public health.
According to Javier Tebas, son of the president of the Spanish Primera Division, the Corona rules established by the football association had not been violated, as the news agency Europa Press and the sports newspaper "Marca" reported.
Before the departure, there were four infected persons until July 19, but they were all isolated and did not travel with them.
Just before the flight on Monday to A Coruña, all players and team members had been re-tested.
When the team was already in A Coruña, "five or six" other team members were positive for the Corona test.
The game was cancelled 60 minutes before the start, Tebas Llanas said.
