Bike pro Tony Martin: career continuation imaginable
Time trial specialist Tony Martin thinks about a continuation of his career.
Frankfurt/Main - The seven-time world champion Tony Martin can well imagine continuing his cycling career.
"I am laying down the framework conditions with the team just how and in what form it could continue," said the 35-year-old of the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung".
Martin is currently employed by the Dutch team Jumbo-Visma and had planned to finish his career after this year before the Corona break.
The negotiations with his team were also about the number of race days, he said.
Or other problems that would plague him as a family father, Martin said.
In the past he got up after a fall, and the first thought was: "Quickly back on the bike.
Today, as the father of a little daughter, I think: What if".
The professional biker admitted that there are aspects with which he is increasingly difficult.
"But it did me good to see from the Corona time what I have on cycling and how much fun it is for me."
At the Tour de l'Ain (5th to 9th August), the time-trial specialist returns to the competition.
Bavaria: At least four deaths on the streets of Bavaria on weekends
The beautiful weather attracts bikers on the streets in many places.
For at least three people, the motorcycle tour ends fatally.
An 18-year-old pedestrian also dies.
Schönthal - In the event of accidents on the streets of Bavaria several, mostly young people died on the weekend.
An 18-year-old motorcyclist was caught on Saturday at Schönthal (Cham County) by a car that came on the opposite track.
At first, it was unclear why the car hit the back lane.
On Saturday in Upper Bavaria, a 22-year-old met with a horse-drawn carriage on his plane.
According to the police, he was traveling downhill at Beilngries.
In a left turn, he bounced against the carriage.
His injuries were so severe that he died at the scene of the accident.
Of the twelve inmates of the carriage, a man was severely injured and a man was slightly injured, as the police reported.
In another fatal accident, an 18-year-old died in Bad Kötzting, Upper Palatine.
He had laid down on a road the night of Sunday and was overrun by a 42-year-old driver.
According to the police, the 18-year-old wanted to sleep.
The driver could not stop in time.
On Saturday, a 57-year-old biker hit a car in a right-hand turn, despite full braking, at Schönberg (Freyung-Grafenau district).
He died at the scene of the accident.
The 57-year-old driver suffered a shock, the remaining three people in the car remained unharmed.
The safety of motorcyclists was discussed on Saturday by Bavarian Minister of Transport Kerstin Schreyer (CSU).
In a letter to the organiser of the Biker protests announced for August against driving bans, Gabor Kovacs, the minister referred to extensive investments such as underrun protection to guardrails and the defusing of dangerous curves.
"We have achieved a lot for the safety of motorcyclists in recent years," the letter said.
"The number of motorized two-wheelers killed decreased by around 28 percent compared to 2011".
