Argentina rejects counter bid by creditors
The new demands could not be met, the Ministry of Economy in Buenos Aires announced on Saturday.
"This would not only be irresponsible, but also unfair," said a statement.
"While 50 percent of the children in Argentina live in poverty, we cannot increase the short-term profits of our creditors."
The debt of the second largest economy in South America is no longer sustainable under current conditions.
Argentina therefore calls on its private creditors to waive some of their claims of around 66 billion US dollars (around 59 billion euros).
If there is no agreement, the country will again face the state bankruptcy.
It would be the ninth default in Argentine history.
Most recently, lenders had asked for higher interest rates on government bonds and changes to some contractual clauses.
However, the Argentinean government remains committed to its last offer and is not prepared to make any further concessions.
Argentina is in a serious financial and economic crisis.
The latest inflation rate was more than 50 percent.
For the current year, experts expect economic power to decline by around ten percent.
At the end of May Argentina had not paid interest receivables of US$503 million and had thus slipped into a limited default.
Professionally arrived - private not yet
"It's going super good" - this is the conclusion Dr. Stefanie Kramer draws after her first days at the Notariat in Eggenfelden.
In the end, everything went very quickly: In mid-May, Dr. Stefanie Kramer learned that she will succeed Lutz Feller at the Eggenfeldener Notariatstelle.
Already six weeks later, at the beginning of July, the graduate lawyer started working, the normal day-to-day business is already running on full speed.
"However, I still have to arrive privately," she explains in conversation with the Rottaler Anzeiger and laughs.
Of course, the short lead time was not enough to move the centre of gravity from Regensburg completely to Eggenfelden, reports the native Dingolfingerin.
She is currently looking for a suitable apartment or a house in the city with her husband, who is a judge at the regional court in Regensburg.
At least her husband could apply for parental leave at short notice in order to ensure the care of the two daughters (31⁄2 and 11⁄2 years old).
In order not to have to commute every day from Regensburg, she has for the time being also an overnight stay with her parents in Dingolfing, explains the 39-year-old.
Grown up in the neighbouring county, the city of Eggenfelden has of course long been a term for her.
When visiting with her family in the past months, she found out again: "Eggenfelden is a really beautiful small town".
She was all the more pleased that she had made the race for the vacant position in the competition.
Her home of Lower Bavaria also plays a central role in Dr. Stefanie Kramer's professional career: After studying law in Passau, she completed her traineeship and the 2nd state examination in Regensburg.
After several stops as a notarassessorin, among others in Rehau and Hof in Oberfranken, Babenhausen in Unterallgäu and Regensburg - at this time she also shouldered "by the way" the doctorate in labour law - she entered in 2012 her first position as notarin in Rotthalmünster in the district of Passau.
In 2016, she went on parental leave, followed by a move to Regensburg.
Since then, she has taken over representation services in various notarial offices.
When the job in Eggenfelden was advertised because of Lutz Feller's imminent retirement, she saw the right time for her full career re-entry, explains the 39-year-old.
The team of its predecessor, who will take over the holiday representation at the Notariatstelle in the future, has taken over Dr. Stefanie Kramer completely - and has a praise for the team of the firm ready: "It's going super good!"
The fact that she can rely on well-established procedures makes it easier for her to take care of the upcoming relocation of the private food point.
She has already made contact with a local institution in terms of kindergarten or crib places.
And if everything works as desired, she hopes to be able to pursue her hobby here soon - and get to know the most beautiful jogging trails of the Rottal.
BVB plans to start the league with a maximum of 15,000 spectators
Dortmund The largest German football stadium in Dortmund will not even be filled with 20 percent at the start of the season in the event of a fan return.
"Due to the distance regulation, which must be complied with, we are planning according to the current situation with 12,000 to 15,000 spectators", said Borussia Dortmund's managing director Carsten Cramer to the "Tagesspiegel".
Normally, the arena in the district city holds a little more than 81,000 spectators at Bundesliga games.
In the ghost games of the last season caused by the Corona pandemic, BVB had lost about four million euros per game.
The Cramer, responsible for marketing, digitisation and internationalization at BVB, hopes that in addition to the normal audience seats, some of the approximately 4000 seats in the hospitality area can be opened again: "It is of course a blow to the account if these revenues break away completely".
In the face of the ongoing Corona crisis, everyone is currently "well advised to take a stable sideline".
"If many companies are not doing well and 6.8 million people are in short-time work alone in Germany, then the need for entertainment is limited," Cramer explained.
The Dortmund marketing boss praised the BVB professionals for their salary waiver, which is supposed to help overcome the crisis: "Of course, the players know that their salary waiver has a different effect than if we put 100 people working in merchandising on short-time work."
Tiny Miracles: Early start to life with a few hundred grams
Hardly heavier than a packerl of butter, just three tablespoons of blood in his entire body: that was Gabriel when he was born - he weighed exactly 273 grams.
The Bub is one of around 400 young children, who are cared for every year at the Grazer Kinderklinik.
A quarter of them weigh less than 1,500 grams, a few - like Gabriel and his brothers Raphael and Michael - are extreme lightweights with not even one kilogram of birth weight.
They are so small and born so early that neither lungs, nor intestines, nor muscles are fully formed.
Their skin is sometimes so tender that they could damage the electrodes of an ECG.
And they are so tiny that they sometimes wear doll clothes and mini diapers specially made for them.
But not so small that they would not be in voice - "and how", Berndt Urlesberger smiles.
"Even though, of course, they don't scream as loud as big babies."
When the whiteboard becomes a stage
Despite Corona Theater in the classroom: The whiteboard as a stage experienced the 9th classes of the St. James Gymnasium in Abtsgmünd just before the start of the holiday.
Actress Julia Sylvester from the Theatre of the City of Aalen presented the production "Das Heimatkleid" to the students by video.
Afterwards, the students were able to talk about the play and the performance via Skype with the actress and the director Winfried Tobias.
The idea for the performance format from the current Corona situation was born.
Teacher Teresa Nar was delighted with the enrichment of the teaching.
Although at the end all the participants agreed that the direct encounter in the theatre and stage room would offer additional attractions, in the theatre one also sees the potential for contact in the schools.
"If we continue to improve the technical framework, this could be an interesting addition to the game," said director Winfried Tobias.
