"From the Wind": film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
The film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
At the age of 104, she died naturally in Paris on Sunday, confirmed her spokesperson for the German Press Agency.
De Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the southern epic "Vom Winde verweht" (1939).
Born as a child of British parents in Tokyo, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as a toddler.
The Austrian theaterman Max Reinhardt discovered the 19-year-old in the role of the Hermia of Shakespeare's "Summer Night's Dream".
The film studio Warner Brothers signed her for seven years and released her at the side of Eroll Flynn.
She made eight films with the heartbreaker.
In 1946, she won her first Oscar in the lead role of "To Each His Own".
The film ran in Germany under the title "Mutterherz".
Three years later, the award came as the best actress in William Wyler's "The Heiress" (the heiress).
She also received much recognition as a neurotic eccentric in "The Dark Mirror" and "The Snake Mine".
In 1952, Daphne du Maurier proposed her for the lead role in the film adaptation of her novel "My Cousin Rachel".
The play became a worldwide success.
With her long-time friend Bette Davis, she played in "Weighing Song for a Body".
He married Marcus Goodrich (1946-1953) and his son Benjamin.
In Paris de Havilland married the journalist Pierre Paul Galante and had his daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage, too, broke up.
Rumours about an affair with former British Prime Minister Edward Heath have never been confirmed.
