In addition to the show tournament, three starting places for the German championships were played in Timmendorfer Strand at the beginning of September: the tickets secured Armin Dollinger/Simon Kulzer, Manuel Harms/Richard Peemüller and Simon Pfretschner/Milan Sievers.
Kalbitz ejection from AfD confirmed - FDP speaks of "fig leaf"
From the FDP's point of view, the exclusion of Andreas Kalbitz from the AfD is only a "fig leaf" and does not change the party's character.
"The AfD is the parliamentary arm of the extreme right in Germany.
Andreas Kalbitz is only part of the tip of the radical iceberg in the AfD," said FDP domestic politician Benjamin Strasser of the news agency dpa in Berlin.
The AfD's federal arbitral tribunal had confirmed on Saturday in Stuttgart, after several hours of trial, the exclusion of Kalbitz, which the Federal Executive Board had decided by a majority in May.
Kalbitz is chairman of the AfD Group in the Brandenburger Landtag.
"If the AfD were really about consistently removing right-wing extremists from its party, officials such as Björn Höcke and his followers would have been excluded long ago," said Strasser.
"However, there is no political will in the AfD because right-wing extremism is now part of the party."
Similarly, CSU Secretary General Markus Blume said: "The fact that Andreas Kalbitz is now excluded says nothing and does not change anything," he said to the "world on Sunday".
"It speaks volumes rather, how many frenetic supporters a far right still has in the middle of the AfD."
Blume expects the AfD to land below five percent in elections in the future.
"The days of the AfD in the parliaments are numbered."
Kalbitz was one of the spokesmen of the officially dissolved "Flügel" around the Thuringian AfD-Landes- and faction chairman Björn Höcke; the constitutional protection classifies the strenght as "secured right-wing extremist endeavour".
In May, the AfD Federal Executive had thrown Kalbitz out of the party.
As a reason, he stated that Kalbitz did not state an earlier membership in the now banned right-wing extreme "Heimattreuen Deutschen Jugend" (HDJ) and the Republicans.
Kalbitz denies his membership in the HDJ.
Sebastian Walter, Chairman of the Left Party in Brandenburg's Landtag, also stressed that the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court did not change the character of the AfD: "The wolf ate only chalk.
The AfD remains a far-right party, whether with or without Kalbitz".
Neither the federal party nor the right wing were weakened by this decision.
"The maneuver of the Meuthen troops is transparent.
One wants to avoid further observation by the constitutional protection and tries to get under the radar," said Walter.
"The AfD won't let go of the spirits she called.
A throw-out doesn't change anything," commented the Brandenburg SPD General Secretary Erik Stohn on the decision in the Kalbitz case.
"Here, the AfD-Landesverband and the faction held to their right-wing leader to this day."
The legal dispute over the membership of Kalbitz in the AfD will continue.
On Saturday, he announced that he would take action against the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court.
North Sea wind farms deliver a good 21 percent more electricity
The wind power plants on the German North Sea have fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid in the first six months of the year.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period of the previous year, said the network operator Tennet in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which do not belong to the network area of Tennet, have supplied a further 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, the wind power from the North and Baltic Sea is 13.73 TWh, compared to 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea thus accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind power in Germany, which is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms ensure higher generation capacity
In addition to the wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from higher generation capacities, as new wind farms have joined the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind power plants in the North Sea were all running at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient; according to Tennet, it is 7.1 gigawatts.
It is expected to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea by 2030.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we will invest 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore network connections by then," said Tennet Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, even at sea, wind farms cannot exploit their capacity, but reach about 40 percent.
The record date this year is 2 January, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce around 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, equivalent to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
