Heal wants to test other industries after meat industry
The Corona crisis brought the conditions to light again in parts of the meat industry.
Legislative intensification is imminent.
But are they right - and will it remain so?
Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to check other industries according to the now planned strict regulations against maladministration in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry for industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary," said Heil of the Deutsche Presse-Agentur in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against general restrictions on works contracts.
After the mass outbreak of Corona at the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet intends to adopt a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to employ foreign personnel when slaughtering, cutting and processing meat.
To this end, the use of contract and temporary workers is to be prohibited there.
Employers' President Ingo Kramer said to the dpa: "Finger away from a general restriction on contracts of employment and leave to employees if one does not want to completely strangle the economy".
Work contracts, for example, are the basis for the customer's added value for large areas of the craft, construction and plant construction industries.
"The errors of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument."
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban work contracts anywhere in the German economy".
Work contracts were useful.
"When an industrial company hires a craftsman to install a safety system, this is a normal work contract."
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary agency work to be unconstitutional in its industry alone.
It is not possible to explain why in future labour law should apply to portioning and packaging cheeses other than sausages, according to a statement on the proposed law, as reported by the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday).
In the event of a ban, the consumer price would increase by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
Many Eastern European employees from works contractors worked in the sector, according to the results of an audit carried out by the NRW Labour Protection Administration, partly 16 hours a day.
Often they didn't have a break.
Wages were retained for protective equipment or rent.
It was also established that the situation with the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively sharp law came into force for the meat industry as early as 2017.
However, "tricky constructions" bypassed them.
"Now needs to be fundamentally cleaned up".
The politician announced: "In the OSH law, which we want to adopt in the cabinet at the end of July, measures are also measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example higher testing rates in the field of occupational safety or clear criteria for community accommodation".
The draft of the dpa includes amendments to the Act on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Health and Safety Act.
Brandenburg's Minister for Consumer Protection Ursula Nunnemacher (Greens) believes that more intensive controls are needed.
"I would like us to be able to do even more controls in many supervisory areas: food controls, animal welfare, all kinds of things, for example, animal transport," said Nunnemacher on Sunday in the RBB broadcast "Brandenburg aktuell".
However, more posts were also needed for more controls.
