Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all threatened penalties and court judgments, drivers continue to gas in countless illegal races on the Baden-Württemberg roads: Last year and the first four months of this year, police have already registered more than 250 illegal car races in the southwest.
There are no comparable figures for the years before, but the racers are increasingly doing work for the judicial authorities: In 2018, 155 investigations were conducted at the prosecution offices between Konstanz and Mannheim for illegal races, one year later it was already 252 and in the current year until the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as indicated by the Ministry of the Interior's response to a request from the Landtag SPD.
In most cases, the drivers had to compete spontaneously against each other or they had taken the flight from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the racers caught and asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed since 2018 and 15 prison sentences have been imposed.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, because of the many tragic accidents and trials of past years, other motorists reacted more sensitively than before and reported more frequently, said a minister's spokesman.
Especially popular with Rasern is the highway 8. Again and again motorists brake out the traffic there in order to get space and use the free track for a race.
Last August a dozen riders were caught near Kirchheim under Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 riders on the A8 at Merklingen.
A81 is the most popular "racing track"
On the A81, the police even registered more races than on any other federal highway.
With a speed limit there is an attempt to slow down the racers on the particularly affected section between narrows and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and emaciated sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers avoid the lawn to Germany because of the high penalties for too fast driving and car races in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit should not be reduced to a few routes: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the transport expert of the SPD parliament.
"The inhibition threshold for Raser would be significantly higher if you weren't allowed to travel here and there legally with 200 kilometers per hour and more."
From enlightenment or image campaigns Rivoir holds less: "Anyone who ignores all rules in such a way and not only puts his own life, but also the lives of other road users at risk, can hardly be reached with reason".
ADAC calls for greater police intervention
On the other hand, this is not enough for the ADAC: "We assume that Raser will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at the ADAC Württemberg.
It calls for additional and tougher controls on the routes concerned.
Not infrequently, the high-touring force measurement becomes more painful and serious: since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died nationwide in the races, two of them uninvolved in a night crash in Stuttgart's city centre and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men were reported to have delivered a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, bounced against a garden wall and remained on the side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 more people were injured in the races of the past two years.
According to Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, however, sharper penalties are not necessary: "Legislative action is not seen in order to penalise illegal motor races more severely," says the paper of the Interior Ministry.
