Nuremberg: Unapproved tuning meeting - police intervenes, 700 vehicles and around 1100 people
Hundreds of cars and over 1000 people took part in a "tuning meeting" on Saturday night in the parking lot of a furniture store.
The police implemented their announcement to strengthen control of such events.
A big tuning meeting took place on Saturday evening (25 July 2020) in Nuremberg's southern city.
Several hundred vehicles were involved.
According to the Mittelfranken police, around 10.30 p.m., the Nuremberg Transport Police found an increased volume of vehicles in the area of a large parking lot on Ingolstädter Straße.
As a result, the police carried out a variety of vehicle checks there.
Only recently, the police had announced that they would step up their efforts against so-called autoposers.
Illegal Tuning Meeting in Nuremberg: Only a small part of the "scene"
The officers were among the top 700 vehicles and about 1100 people, the police counted.
Of this, however, only a small part of those present are to be attributed to the "autoposer" and tuning scene.
Apparently, the majority of the relevant scene followed the police's appeal.
On the basis of the vehicles and persons on site, it can be assumed that they were mainly spectators.
In addition, the majority of those present adhered to the current infection protection regulations, in particular the observance of the minimum distance and the wearing of a mouth-wet protection.
The on-the-spot checks were completed around 1:00 a.m.
In total, the officials found that 10 vehicles had undergone such structural changes that the type-approval had expired.
Four of these vehicles had to be secured.
No car races
Illegal car races didn't exist.
"The Central Franconia Police Bureau will continue to keep an eye on what is happening and will continue to carry out increased control measures, including in connection with the emergence of spectators," it said.
The agency News5 spoke with Jürgen Schrödinger from the towing company involved: "They all have beautiful rims, we must not scratch them," says Schrödinger.
That's what special tapes would be used for.
Also because the cars are wider, the company must be careful not to damage.
"The young people should finally get their cars back unharmed."
Employment agency figures: 900 suspected short-time abuse cases
Berlin - According to the Federal Employment Agency (BA), around 900 suspected cases of abuse of short-time work allowances are investigated.
"This is extremely low for more than 880,000 companies that have indicated short-time work," said Daniel Terzenbach, CEO of the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, responsible for operating business.
When a large number of companies suddenly applied for short-time work at the beginning of the Corona crisis, the BA had to react quickly.
Normally, the exam lasts up to three weeks.
"We didn't have that much time at our disposal in this hot phase.
So we'll take a closer look at the final accounts.
I'm sure there'll be a lot more to do.
We are not naive and have a long breath".
Evidence of abuse often comes from the employees or trade unions concerned.
In addition, the BA uses analysis software to detect abuse patterns.
According to Terzenbach, the BA is preparing for a possible wave of insolvency in the autumn.
"Will there be significantly more insolvencies than in the previous year?
The assessments differ, but we prepare ourselves for the case and already train our employees in the employment agencies for the processing of applications for insolvency money".
The figures are still inconspicuous, said Terzenbach.
World Heritage in Potsdam: Party in the New Garden dissolved
Potsdam - On Friday evening about 40 young people celebrated a party in the New Garden.
The collection had been dissolved at 8:48 p.m. by the drivers of the Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation (SPSG), the foundation informed on PNN request.
The young people would have left the park.
On Saturday evening some youths would have played rugby in the New Garden.
The meadow had been cleared by precinct drivers, said SPSG spokesman Frank Kallensee on Sunday.
Again and again there are illegal celebrations in the parks
In the Parks of the Foundation, there are always accumulations, where the distance and hygiene rules Covid-19-Vergangverordnung are not complied with.
At the end of June there was a celebration with about 300 people in the park Babelsberg, a week later about 150 people celebrated in the New Garden.
Even without Corona regulations, the parks are closed at nightfall.
Camping on the meadows is prohibited according to the parking regulations, there are only a few exceptions.
