Austria: Mass tests after Corona outbreak in tourist destination
With hundreds of tests, authorities have responded to a Corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang.
The number of confirmed cases increased to 48, according to the state authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
According to this, many of the infected young interns are in tourism companies, but at least one holiday guest was tested positively.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodation on Saturday night.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations there and there" of bookings, said the head of the tourist board Wolfgangsee, Hans Wieser, the dpa.
Some guests also left early.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist resort in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season around a third of the guests are German.
On Friday, the first infections had become public.
The head of the district office, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behaviour of the interns, who had celebrated in several places and might have infected themselves there.
"We all enjoyed doing this in our youth," he told the radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The Tourist Board launched an information campaign to raise awareness among young employees about the dangers of Covid-19.
From Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from July 15th were contacted.
The outbreak evokes memories of the Austrian ski and party town of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a centre of Corona spread throughout Europe in the early phase of the pandemic.
A total of more than 1500 people are currently infected with the virus in Austria.
The focus of the new infections is on Vienna and Upper Austria.
