North Korea shuts down border town after Corona suspected case
North Korea has so far seen its own measures to combat the corona virus as a "bright success".
Now the country reports for the first time on a suspected case.
Due to a first official Corona suspicion in the country, North Korea has completely sealed off a big city for fear of disaster.
Despite the strictest epidemiological measures in the past six months, "the malignant virus could have been introduced into the country," the state media reported.
For the region around the border town of Kaesong, the state of emergency had been imposed.
The communist leadership called out the highest alarm level.
If the suspected case is confirmed, it would be the first official infection case with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
North Korea had not registered a single infection, according to its own statements, and had described its defences as "enlightening success".
The data were questioned abroad.
Symptoms of the disease were reported to have been identified by a "outlier" who had illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on July 19.
The person had left for South Korea three years ago and had now returned across the border.
For the crossing within the four-kilometre-wide and mostly still mined military buffer zone, there was at first no confirmation from South Korea.
However, according to reports from the national news agency Yonhap, South Korea's military admitted the possibility of illegal border crossing to North Korea as high.
There were tests on some people.
North Korea reportedly called for an urgent meeting of the workers' political bureau chaired by Kim Jong Un on Saturday because of the suspicions.
The "dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive disaster."
Kim had already ordered on Friday as a preventive measure "to block Kaesong completely and isolate each district and region from others", it continued.
The person concerned and all the people in Kaesong who had had contact with her had been quarantined.
The central military commission of the party is therefore to investigate the "outlier fall" as well as the behaviour of the responsible military unit and, if necessary, impose severe punishment.
Kaesong is estimated to have about 300,000 people.
