Hurricane "Hanna" reaches Texas: Help complicated because of Corona
Washington - The first hurricane of this year's season over the Atlantic has hit land in Texas.
Life-threatening floods, strong winds and heavy rains now threatened parts of the U.S. state, the National Hurricane Centre of the U.S. climate agency NOAA announced at night on Sunday (local time).
Governor Greg Abbott declared an emergency for numerous districts.
The Corona pandemic, which is raging in Texas, makes the work of the helpers more difficult, said Abbott, according to the US media.
Evacuated called for caution
"Every hurricane is an enormous challenge," said Abbott according to the newspaper "Houston Chronicle".
With regard to the cyclone in Texas, he added: "This challenge is complicated and aggravated, considering that it sweeps through an area that is the most affected area of the state by Covid-19."
According to Johns Hopkins University, about 5,000 people have died in Texas alone as a result of the Corona pandemic.
Abbott called for caution to people who had to leave their homes.
They should not disregard practices "to which we have become accustomed", such as wearing masks, said the governor according to CBS.
It is important that everyone kept his distance.
Therefore, hotel rooms were also provided in some places.
In addition, Corona should be tested in emergency shelters.
Damage had initially only been reported from the coastal town of Port Mansfield.
Storm warning withdrawn again
At wind speeds of up to 150 kilometers per hour, "Hanna" was hit by land on the island of Padre Island just off the Texan coast, according to the authorities.
The tropical storm had previously been upgraded to the lowest-level hurricane.
For the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent, a storm flood warning had been issued and later withdrawn.
Authorities expected a weakening, while "Hanna" continues to move inland and towards the northeast of Mexico.
"Douglas" moves towards Hawaii
In the Pacific, Hurricane "Douglas" was on Sunday at wind speeds of around 150 kilometers per hour in the direction of Hawaii.
The Hurricane Center, however, expected it to continue to weaken.
According to forecasts, it is said to be near the largest islands of Hawaii on Sunday (local time) - then as a storm just below the hurricane threshold.
Over the Atlantic, NOAA expected an above-average Hurricane season this year, according to a May forecast.
From June to the end of November, up to ten hurricanes could be expected, of which up to six could be very strong hurricanes, the authority had declared.
On average, there are six hurricanes per year over the Atlantic, three of them developing into storms of great strength.
In view of available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and the Caribbean, the probability of a normal season is only 30 percent, which is only 10 percent below average, it was said at the time.
US President Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that his government is closely monitoring the storms and in contact with the affected states.
