Formula 1 needs a special rule to select its world champion
Since it cannot be driven on the required number of continents, the FIA has to improvise in order to award the World Cup titles.
All America races were cancelled, however.
Race calendar is becoming more and more concrete
The racing calendar of the current Formula 1 season continues to take shape.
Three more race tracks were added to the ten confirmed Grand Prix races during the week.
In October, it is planned to drive at the Nürburgring in Germany and Portimão in Portugal.
On November 1, Lewis Hamilton and Co. will fight for World Cup points on the Italian traditional race track in Imola.
This means that the 2020 racing calendar comprises 13 races according to the current status.
"We are pleased that we are continuing to make great progress in completing our plans for the 2020 season," said Formula 1 boss Chase Carey.
In total, 15 to 18 races in the top class of motorsport are to be completed in this exceptional season.
The Formula 1 season is scheduled to end in Asia.
The final race calendar will be fixed and published in the coming weeks.
Before the already officially planned races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December, according to media reports, there could still be appearances in Vietnam and Malaysia at the end of November.
Regulations demands races on three continents
The Formula 1 regulations, however, require races on three continents for the award of the World Championship.
Even if, as currently planned, only two continents are driven, there is to be a world champion.
With the help of a special rule, the FIA wants to award the title on the basis of "extraordinary circumstances" due to the Coronavirus pandemic.
The traditional start of the season in Australia in March had to be cancelled in the short term due to the imminent Corona crisis.
A return to the continent this year is not an issue.
In addition, Formula 1 will not be a guest in America this year.
Rejection meets criticism in Brazil
Due to the tense Corona situation, the races will not take place in Canada, the USA, Mexico and Brazil.
"We look forward to being with them again next season," said Carey.
The rejection of the Americas races met with criticism, especially in Brazil: "The rejection did not come as a surprise to us, but we cannot accept the reasons for it," said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in São Paulo.
Thus, the number of infections in the São Paulo region is significantly lower than in other regions of Brazil.
Moreover, the concerns of some teams not wanting to drive in Brazil would not justify a rejection.
It was prepared for the required security measures.
