Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green died
His life was like a roller coaster ride: After a rapid ascent with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly up again.
Now Bluesrock guitarist Peter Green died at the age of 73.
Ingenious guitarist, drug junkie, cult follower: Peter Green, co-founder of Fleetwood Mac, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73 years, family members announced in an official statement on Saturday that another statement would be announced for the next few days.
Top musicians like Peter Frampton praised Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
Mick Fleetwood spoke in an emotional reaction of a "monumental loss" for all former and current members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
The drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green had founded the legendary band in London in 1967, until today his dreamy instrumental hit "Albatross" is unforgettable.
The life of the musician ("The End Of The Game", "In The Skies") was like a roller coaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac Green experienced a rapid rise - the band celebrated their greatest successes but then without him.
Among other things, there was a dispute because Green wanted to donate all the profits to the group for charitable purposes.
He began to perform in wide robes and with large crucifixes.
Mental problems are also said to have played a role.
Green left the band three years after its foundation in 1970.
A social descent followed.
The bluesrock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
For a long time, Green was treated in psychiatry.
During most of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived temporarily on the street, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent a while in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 as the son of a Jewish working-class family in the London district of Bethnal Green.
Already at a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians like B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven he learned the first guitar grips.
At the age of 15 the teenager began playing guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to stand on stage as a lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later he was hired as a substitute for his idol Eric Clapton in the Bluesbreakers.
In the middle of the Blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross" composed by Green brought the group the first number one hit in winter 1968/69 and catapulted it to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid rise soon showed its shadows: Green could not cope with the media rumble, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on the life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that happened to me in life is the drugs - the best thing was to land a number one hit."
Towards the end of the decade, Green was surprisingly successful in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Meanwhile Fleetwood Mac swam on a wave of success without him in new formation.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite several small solo successes, Green didn't make a big comeback until he started out with a group of friends in 1996.
The British "Daily Telegraph" then spoke of a rock star who returned to Earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band dissolved in 2004.
For music experts he was a blues legend already in his lifetime - and with his soft sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
